<article id=3D"content" role=3D"main">

<!-- #BeginEditable "Body" -->=20


<h1 class=3D"center">Ratios</h1>=20


<h3 class=3D"center">A ratio <b>compares</b> <b>values</b>.</h3>=20

<p>A ratio tells us how much of one thing there is compared to another.</p>=
=20
<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/numbers/images/r=
atio-3-1.svg" alt=3D"ratio 3:1" height=3D"154" width=3D"316"><br>
<span class=3D"larger">There are 3 blue squares to 1 yellow square</span></=
p>=20
<p>Ratios can be shown in different ways:</p>

	<table style=3D"border: 0; margin:auto;">
		<tbody><tr>
			<td style=3D"text-align:right;"><span class=3D"large">Use the ":" to sep=
arate the values:</span></td>
			<td style=3D"width:20px;">&nbsp;</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;"><span class=3D"larger">3 : 1</span></td=
>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td style=3D"text-align:right;">&nbsp;</td>
			<td>&nbsp;</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">&nbsp;</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td style=3D"text-align:right;"><span class=3D"large">Or we can use the =
word "to":</span></td>
			<td>&nbsp;</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;"><span class=3D"larger">3 to 1</span></t=
d>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td style=3D"text-align:right;">&nbsp;</td>
			<td>&nbsp;</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">&nbsp;</td>
		</tr>=20
<!--<tr>
			<td style=3D"text-align: right;" ><span class=3D"large">Or write it like=
 a fraction:</span></td>
			<td>&nbsp;</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;"><span class=3D"intbl larger"><em>3</em>=
<strong>1</strong></span></td>
		</tr> -->
	</tbody></table>=20
<p>They mean the same thing: 3 of the first thing for every 1 of the second=
 thing.</p>=20
<p>A ratio can be scaled up:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center larger"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/numbers/i=
mages/ratio-3-1b.svg" alt=3D"ratio 3:1 is also 6:2" height=3D"234" width=3D=
"316"><br>
Here the ratio is also <span class=3D"larger"> 3 blue squares to 1 yellow s=
quare,<br>
even though there are more squares. </span></p>=20

<h3>Try it Yourself</h3>=20

<p>Use the slider below to create different ratios and see how they look.</=
p>=20

<iframe width=3D"100%" height=3D"269px" scrolling=3D"no" title=3D"JavaScrip=
t Animation" style=3D"display: block; margin: auto; border: none; backgroun=
d-color: transparent; overflow: hidden; transition: 0.6s ease-in-out; max-w=
idth: 100%;"></iframe><div class=3D"script" style=3D"height: 260px; display=
: none;">images/ratio-slider.js</div>
<p>Can you make a ratio of 5:2? How about 1:4?</p>=20


<h2>Using Ratios</h2>=20

<p>The key to working with ratios is to always multiply or divide both numb=
ers by the same value. This keeps the relationship between the quantities t=
he same.</p>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example:</h3>

	<table style=3D"border: 0; margin:auto;">
		<tbody><tr>
			<td>=20

	<p><b>4 : 5</b> is the same as<b> 4</b>=C3=972<b> : 5</b>=C3=972<b> <em>=
=3D</em> 8 : 10</b></p></td>
			<td style=3D"width:30px;">&nbsp;</td>
			<td><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/numbers/images/ratio-times-2.=
svg" alt=3D"ratio 4:5 times 2 is 8:10" height=3D"91" width=3D"80"></td>
		</tr>
	</tbody></table>=20
</div>=20

<h3>Recipes</h3>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<div class=3D"floatRt"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/numbers/imag=
es/pancakes.jpg" alt=3D"pancakes" height=3D"149" width=3D"250"></div>

<h3>Example: A Recipe for pancakes uses 3 cups of flour and 2 cups of milk.=
</h3>=20

<p class=3D"center">So the ratio of flour to milk is <b>3 : 2</b></p>=20
<p>To make pancakes for a LOT of people we need 4 times the quantity, so we=
 multiply the numbers by 4:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center"><b>3</b>=C3=974<b> : 2</b>=C3=974<b> <em>=3D</em> 12 : =
8</b></p>=20
<p><b>In other words, 12 cups of flour and 8 cups of milk</b>.</p>=20
<p>The ratio is still the same, so the pancakes should be just as yummy.</p=
>=20
</div>=20


<h2>"Part-to-Part" and "Part-to-Whole" Ratios</h2>=20

<p>The examples so far have been "part-to-part" (comparing one part to anot=
her part).</p>=20
<p>But a ratio can also show a part compared to the <b>whole lot</b>.</p>=
=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: There are 5 pups, 2 are boys, and 3 are girls</h3>=20

	<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/images/art/sage=
-five-pups.svg" alt=3D"five pups" height=3D"171" width=3D"235"></p>=20
	<p class=3D"larger">Part-to-Part:</p>=20
	<p class=3D"center">The ratio of boys to girls is <span class=3D"larger">2=
:3</span></p>=20
	<p class=3D"center">The ratio of girls to boys is <span class=3D"larger">3=
:2</span></p>=20
	<p class=3D"larger">Part-to-Whole:</p>=20
	<p class=3D"center">The ratio of boys to <b>all</b> pups is <span class=3D=
"larger">2:5</span> or <span class=3D"frac-large"><sup>2</sup>/<sub>5</sub>=
</span></p>=20
	<p class=3D"center">The ratio of girls to <b>all</b> pups is <span class=
=3D"larger">3:5</span> or <span class=3D"frac-large"><sup>3</sup>/<sub>5</s=
ub></span></p>=20
	<div class=3D"gap"></div>

</div>=20


<h2>Try It Yourself</h2>=20

<iframe width=3D"100%" height=3D"303px" scrolling=3D"no" title=3D"JavaScrip=
t Animation" style=3D"display: block; margin: auto; border: none; backgroun=
d-color: transparent; overflow: hidden; transition: 0.6s ease-in-out; max-w=
idth: 100%;"></iframe><div class=3D"script" style=3D"height: 300px; display=
: none;"> images/ratio.js</div>


<h2>Scaling</h2>=20

<p>We can use ratios to scale drawings up or down (by multiplying or dividi=
ng).</p>=20
<div class=3D"beach">

	<table style=3D"border: 0; margin:auto;">
		<tbody><tr>
			<td style=3D"text-align:right;">=20
<p>The height to width ratio of the Indian Flag is <b>2:3</b></p>=20
<p>So for every <b>2</b> (inches, meters, whatever) of height<br>
there should be <b>3</b> of width.</p></td>
			<td><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/numbers/images/indian-flag.jp=
g" alt=3D"indian flag" height=3D"77" width=3D"116"></td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td colspan=3D"2" style=3D"text-align: right;">=20
<p class=3D"center">If we made the flag 20 inches high, it should be 30 inc=
hes wide.</p>=20
<p class=3D"center">If we made the flag 40 cm high, it should be 60 cm wide=
 (which is still in the ratio 2:3)</p></td>
		</tr>
	</tbody></table>=20
</div>=20

<div class=3D"gap"></div>

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: To draw a horse at 1/10th normal size, <b>multiply all sizes =
by 1/10th</b></h3>=20

	<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/numbers/images/=
scale-horse.svg" alt=3D"scale horse" height=3D"199" width=3D"391"></p>=20
	<div style=3D"clear:both"></div>

<p>This horse in real life is 1500 mm high and 2000 mm long, so the ratio o=
f its <b>height to length</b> is</p>=20
<p class=3D"center large">1500 : 2000</p>=20
<p><b>What is that ratio when <span class=3D"center">we</span> draw it at 1=
/10th normal size?</b></p>


<div class=3D"two">
	<div class=3D"lt">1500 : 2000</div>
	<div class=3D"rt">=3D 1500<b> =C3=97 1/10</b> : 2000<b> =C3=97 1/10</b></d=
iv>
	<div class=3D"lt"></div>
	<div class=3D"rt">=3D <b>150 : 200</b></div>
</div>


</div>=20

<div class=3D"simple"></div>

<p>We can make any reduction/enlargement we want that way.</p>=20


<h2>Big Foot?</h2>=20

<div class=3D"floatLt"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/numbers/image=
s/allie-foot.jpg" alt=3D"Foot" height=3D"124" width=3D"220"></div>
<p>Allie measured her foot and found it was 21cm long. Then she measured he=
r Mom's foot and it was 24cm long.</p>=20
<p class=3D"center"><i>"I must have big feet, my foot is nearly as long as =
my Mom's!"</i></p>=20
<p>But then she thought to measure heights, and found she is 133cm tall, an=
d her Mom is 152cm tall.</p>=20
<p>In a table this is:</p>=20
<div class=3D"simple">

	<table style=3D"border: 0; margin:auto;">
		<tbody><tr style=3D"text-align:center;">
			<td style=3D"text-align:right; width:120px;">&nbsp;</td>
			<td style=3D"width:70px;">Allie</td>
			<td style=3D"width:70px;">Mom</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td style=3D"text-align:right;">Length of Foot:</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:right; width:70px;">21cm</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:right; width:70px;">24cm</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td style=3D"text-align:right;">Height:</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:right; width:70px;">133cm</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:right; width:70px;">152cm</td>
		</tr>
	</tbody></table>=20
</div>=20

<p>The "foot-to-height" ratio in fraction style is:</p>

	<table style=3D"border: 0; margin:auto;">
		<tbody><tr>
			<td><span class=3D"larger">Allie:</span></td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;"><span class=3D"intbl large"><em>21</em>=
<strong>133</strong></span></td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center; width:30px;">&nbsp;</td>
			<td class=3D"larger center">Mom:</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;"><span class=3D"intbl large"><em>24</em>=
<strong>152</strong></span></td>
		</tr>
	</tbody></table>=20
<p>We can <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/simplifying-fractions.html"=
>simplify</a> those fractions like this:</p>

	<table style=3D"border: 0; margin:auto;">
		<tbody><tr>
			<td><span class=3D"larger">Allie:</span></td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;"><span class=3D"intbl large"><em>21/7</e=
m><strong>133/7</strong></span></td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center; width:30px;">&nbsp;</td>
			<td class=3D"larger center">Mom:</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;"><span class=3D"intbl large"><em>24/8</e=
